  "body": "## Simple Summary\r\nAllow obtaining the maximum size/capacity of an array or other \"sized\" structure as a constant\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\nSometime it is useful to know the size of a structure or datatype (looking forward to #1440 as well) as a constant. Allow using `size(type)` as a function that produces constant values at compile time that show the allocated size of an object.\r\n\r\n## Specification\r\nAs an example, let's say we have a struct defined as follows:\r\n```python\r\nstruct MyStruct:\r\n    a: address  # uses 1 32-byte word\r\n    b: bytes32  # uses 1 32-byte word\r\n    c: uint256  # uses 1 32-byte word\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe would define `size(MyStruct)` as returning a `constant` value of `96`. We could then define a bytes-encoded version of this struct as follows:\r\n```python\r\ndef takes_mystruct(data: bytes[size(MyStruct)]) -> MyStruct\r\n    return MyStruct({\r\n        a: convert(data[  :32], address),\r\n        d: convert(data[32:64], bytes32),\r\n        c: convert(data[64:  ], uint256),\r\n    })\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Backwards Compatibility\r\nNo backwards compatibility issues\r\n\r\n## Dependencies\r\nNo dependencies\r\n\r\n## References\r\nNo references\r\n\r\n## Copyright\r\nCopyright and related rights waived via [CC0](https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/)\r\n",
